My assumption is that the error message `Expected to read a START_MAP but instead have: END` is caused by a page that was loaded okay, but then changed (due to some JavaScript perhaps), and Selenium&#39;s internal map does match the DOM any more. It actually looks like it&#39;s suddenly turned into an empty page. So this is may the same cause as with the `StaleElementReferenceException`, but it happens even before the element has been found. 

Or maybe it&#39;s something completely different.

However, while I haven&#39;t really found out the root cause, I have found a way to successfully work around the problem. When the `WebDriverException` occurs, it turned out to be a successful approach to start over from loading the page.

I therefore created a wrapper function that would `try` and `catch` the `WebDriverException`, then wait a second and try again. In my tests, it was always enough to retry just once.

Simple example:
````
	public void normalLogin() {
    	driver.get(getBaseUrl() + location);
	    driver.findElement(By.id(&quot;password&quot;).sendKeys(getPassword());
	    driver.findElement(By.id(&quot;authenticateButton&quot;).click();
    }

    public void stableLogin() {
		try {
			normalLogin();
		}
		catch (WebDriverException driverE) {
			System.err.println(&quot;Caught a WebDriverException, retrying&quot;);
			// wait a little 
			try {
	             Thread.sleep(1000);
	        } catch (final InterruptedException e) {
	        	 Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
	        }
			// then try again
            normalLogin();
		}
    }
````

Note that the second attempt won&#39;t be caught any more, because I haven&#39;t had a case where repeating only once wouldn&#39;t haven been enough.

